[2
Date: Wed, 9 Sep 1998 12:06:52 -0400
From: GUJARAT INSTITUTE OF DEVE [SMTP:gidr@ad1.vsnl.net.in
Via: Darshana Vyas <dvyas@counterpart.org>
Source: The Times of India, Ahmedabad, 9 Sep 1998.

In a surprising development, the state government run Food and Drugs
laboratory at Vadodara on Tuesday ruled out the presence of argemone, the
agent which causes dropsy, in all the 18 random samples of ground nut and
palmolein edible oil.
Joint Commissioner of FDL K.M. Bhatt said on Tuesday that both the primary
and secondary tests have confirmed that the samples picked of groundnut
from Godhra district and palmolein sent from Ahmedabad were free from
Argemone Mexicana.
In Ahmedabad, state health minister Ashok Bhatt claimed that results of
seven more samples of palmolein oil were awaited. The case of a man and his
daughter who were affected by dropsy within four days of consuming the
adulterated oil was not [consistent with [reports of others afflicted
with dropsy in Sabarkantha district, he admitted. So far 16 cases of dropsy
have been detected, none in the past 24 hours . The incubation of dropsy
from contamination to full visibility of symptoms was 20 days and this
needed to be investigated, according to the minister.
